# Unit Overview

<div style="background-color: #C6E3E7; border-radius: 40px; color: #000000; width: 95%; padding: 10px 10px 10px 10px;"> <p style="line-height: 1.5; margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 18px;">Problem Solving and Computing is a <b>highly interactive and collaborative</b> introduction to the field of computer science, as framed within the broader pursuit of solving problems.
</p></div>
<br>

#### In the first part of the unit, students practice using a <b>problem solving process</b> to address a series of puzzles, challenges, and real-world scenarios. Next, students learn how computers <b>input, output, store, and process (IOSP)</b> information to help humans solve problems. The unit concludes with a project in which students design an application that helps solve a problem of their choosing.

<img src="https://images.code.org/bd7a10ac7cf259ed7284cc0bcd23e13c-image-1650060916845.15.01 PM.png" alt="Image of input, output, storage, processing process"  style="width:450px; float: right; margin-left:10px; margin-right:10px; margin-top:20px;">

## **Students will:**

* #### Identify the defined characteristics of a computer and how it is used to solve information problems. 
* #### Use a structured problem solving process to address problems and design solutions that use computing technology. 
* #### Create a collaborative classroom environment where students view computer science as relevant, fun, and empowering.
<br>

#### You can view the <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1MdzbIovdWzLimQZeYkWNIC614J_tshmhrKnt-7ne-48/view" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Unit Guide</a> and <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1wNaYFmhH62KfkSjDY9zLat5bwwK4nuvKChJasvSMHeM/view" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Guide to Implementation</a> for more information about this unit

## **Implementation Guidance** 
#### Alternate lessons are provided for some lessons in Unit 1, depending on your classroom context.


### **Suggested time to complete the unit:** 3 weeks 
#### The suggested time is based on 225 instructional minutes per week. Visit the <a href="https://studio.code.org/s/csd1-2024" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Unit Overview Page</a> and use the unit calendar to adjust the instructional minutes to reflect the time you have with your students each week. 
___

